ACCIDENT HAPPENED IN A SECLUDED AREA HOWEVER AS A PRECAUTION PEOPLE WERE RELOCATED TO A COMMUNITY CENTER.  I SPOKE WITH PROPER PEOPLE THERE ANDTHEY DID NOT KNOW ANYTHIND HAD HAPPENED. column168: A DUMP TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM MILES, INC LOCATED AT 85OO WEST BAY ROAD IN BAYTON, TX TO CLEAN HARBORS TECHNOLOGY CORP. LOCATED 5 MILES SOUTH ON HIGHWAY 71 IN KIMBAL, NE.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DISPOSAL FACILITY, IT  WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE REAR DOOR OF THE DUMP TRAILER ONTO PAVEMENT. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY MOVED THE TRAILER ONTO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT WHERE IT WAS ACCEPTED AND PROCESSED.  ALL FREE LIQUIDS WERE ABSORBED WITH A SUITABLE ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND DISPOSED OF AT THE FACILITY INDICATD ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT RAINWATER ENTERED THE CARGO CARRYING PORTION OF THE VEHICLE DURING TRANSIT.  THIS LIQUID THEN ESCAPED FORM A SMALL TEAR IN THE POLYETHYLENE LINER USED WITHIN THE DUMP TRAILER.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FORM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LIQUID WAS OBSERVED.  IN ADDITION, ALL CLOSURES WERE SECURE AND IN PLACE.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, LOADING PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT A LAYEROF SPEEDI DRY IS PLACED AT THE REAR DOOR OF EACH DUMP TRAILER TO ABSORB ANY FREE LIQUID THAT COULD ACCUMULATE IN THE CARGO CARRYING PORTION OF THE VEHICLE.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1120 HRS ON AUGUST 11, 1995, A CONRAIL EMPLOYEE WORKING AT FRONTIER YARD REPORTED WHITE SMOKE ON TRACK 047 CLASS WEST CAR. THIS OCCURRED DURING A HEAVY RAIN STORM. UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAR HAD A RUPTURED DISK. NO PRODUCT LOSS ON GROUND AND SMOKE WAS FROM PRODUCT ON SIDE OF CAR. RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM CONSIGNEE PVS CHEMICALS, RONALD REZZOLINI REPLACED RUPTURED DISK AT 4:15 P.M.

COMPANY TRACTOR TRAILER LOADED WITH 330 GALLON PLASTIC TOTE TANKS CONTAINING VARIOUS CHEMICALS WAS ON INTERSTATE 84 EASTBOUND. OUR UNIT PASSED A TRACTOR TRAILER BELONGING TO TATE TRANSPORTATION. A FEW MILES LATER THE TATE TRUCK PULLED ALONGSIDE OUR TRUCK AND NOTIFIED OUR DRIVER THAT A CHEMICAL WAS RUNNING OUT OF THE BACK OF HIS TRAILER. OUR DRIVER TURNED OFF AT THE NEXT EXIT, NORTH POWDER, OR. UPON EXAMINATION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE VALVE FITTING ON THE END OF THE REARMOST TANK, WAS LOOSE AND WAS LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF CHEMICAL. THE NORTH POWDER FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED AND RESPONDED. THEY IN TURN CALLED THE HAZMAT EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS OUT OF LA GRANDE AND ONTARIO OREGON. THE OREGON STATE POLICE ALSO RESPONDED. THE SMALL CAFE WAS EVACUATED FOR 5 HOURS. OUR DRIVER BUILT AN EARTHEN DIKE AROUND THE SPILLED CHEMICAL ON THE GROUND TO CONTAIN IT. A TOTAL OF SEVEN GALLONS WAS LOST OUT OF THE TANK. GREAT WESTERN CHEMICAL, THE SHIPPER AND RECEIVER OF THE CHEMICALS, THEN ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AND TIGHTENED UP THE LOOSE FITTING, STOPPED THE LEAK, AND CLEANED UP ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WITH AN ABSORBENT PRODUCT AND REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL. AN AMBULANCE WAS CALLED AND TREATED THE TATE DRIVER FOR THROAT DISCOMFORT.

TWENTY DRUMS FOR EXPORT WERE LOADED ON THE FLOOR IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER AT NALCO CHEMICAL COMPANY IN SUGARLAND FOR TRANSPORTATION TO THE MANCHESTER TERMINAL. ADDITIONAL LOADING WAS BEING LOADED AT ELITE AIR FREIGHT, 16440 AIR CENTER. ONE PALLET LOAD OF MATERIAL WAS LOADED WITHOUT INCIDENT. UPON LOADING THE SECOND PALLET, THE FORKS OF THE FORKLIFT EXTENDED BEYOND THE PALLET. ONE FORK PUNCTURED A STEEL DRUM APPROXIMATELY TWO INCHES ABOVE THE BOTTOM. THE CONTENTS SPILLED FROM THE DRUM AND THE TRAILER ONTO A CONCRETE SLAB. SAND WAS USED FIRST TO DIKE AROUND A STORM DRAIN THEN TO ABSORB MATERIAL ON THE PAVEMENT. A HAZ-MAT CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED IN TO COMPLETE THE CLEAN UP AND PROPER DISPOSAL.
DURING THE DURING THE UNLOADING OF THE BOX TRUCK IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A CONTAINER OF AQUEOUS BRAKE CLEANER HAD FALLEN OFF OF THE PALLET AND RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS OF BRAKE CLEANER.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR VEHICLE ENROUTE TO DELIVER A LOAD TO GE SPECIALITY CHEMICALS PLANT IN MORGANTOWN, WV, TRAVELING NORTH ON FAIRMONT RAOD IN WESTOVER GOING UP A SLIGHT INCLINE ON A STRAIGHT ROAD, TRAVELING AT APPROXIMATELY 20MPH WHEN THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE VEHICLE TRAVELLED FOO THE PAVEMENT AND ONTO A SOFT SHOULDER AND SANK INTO THE SOFT SHOULDER NAD DITCH.  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER LAID AT AN APPROX. 45 ANGLE WHICH CAUSED A SMALL AMOUNT OF CARGO TO LEAK THROUGH A CLEAN OUT VENT ON TOP OF THE TRAILER THAT HAD A LOOSE CAP.  THE CARGO WAS CONTAINED IN A BUCKET AND THE CAP WAS TIGHTENED WITH NO FURTHER LOSS.  THE WESTOVER CITY POLICE HAD ADVISED THAT APPROX. 20 PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED ND HAD ALSO CLOSED SEVERAL AREA BUSINESSES AS A PRE-CAUTION.  THE INVESTIGATING OFFICER CONFIRMED ATHAT THERE WERE NO OTHER VEHICLES INVOLVED AND NO INJURIES AND THAT THE GREATEST THREAT WAS FORM THE DIESEL FUEL BECAUSE THE FUEL LINES ON THE TRACTOR HAD BEEN CUT WHEN IT WENT INTO THE DITCH.  THE FAIRMONT ROAD HAD BEEN BLOCKED OFF AND THE COUNTY HAZMAT SQUAD, TECHNICIANS FORM GE SPECIALTY CHEMICALS, THE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION OF INSPECTOR, WESTOVER CITY POLICE DEPT, BLANDDS TOWING, WESTOVER VOL FIRE DEPT, AND MONONGALIA COUNTY VOL FIREMAN'S ASSOCIATION WERE PRESENT AS WE TRANSFERED THE CARGO FROM OUR TRAILER TO A SUBSTITUTE TRAILER FURNISHED BY CHEMICAL LEAMAN TANK LINES, INC.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM MAGNECTICS, DIVISION OF SPANG AND COMPANY LOCATED AT 200 10TH STREET IN EAST BUTLER, PA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP TO OBTAIN REST. PRIOR TO ENTERING THE SLEEPER BERTH COMPARTMENT, THE DRIVER CONDUCTED A LOAD CHECK AND DISCOVERED THAT APROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP BUNG CAP OF THE DRUM ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED HIS DISPATCHER WHO DISPATCHED A CLEAN-UP CREW DISCOVERED THAT THE GASKET BETWEEN THE DRUM AND THE BUNG CAP HAD FAILED DUE TO IT BEING INCOMPATIBLE WITH THE LADING. THIS ALLOWED THE MATERIAL TO ESCAPE FROM THE TOP BUNG OF THE DRUM. THE CREW THEN ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY, OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM AND PLACED ALL CLEAN UP DEBRIS INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM FOR DISPOSAL AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE MANIFEST. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND. IN ADDITION, THE SHIPPER OF THE WASTE WILL BE INSTRUCTED TO UTILIZED BUNG CAPS WHICH ARE COMPATIBLE WITH THE MATERIAL BEING SHIPPED.

DISPOSAL FACILITY DISCOVERED A DRUM LEAKING DUE TO A PUNCTURE OR DEFECT IN THE LINING. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP IMMEDIATELY. THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED TO STOP THE LEAK AND WILL BE DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.

TRAILER ORIGINALLY DROPPED ENROUTE ON 8/04/95. WEEKEND INSPECTIONS FOUND NO SPILLS. YARD INSPECTION ON 8/07/95 FOUND A SPILL UNDER SAID TRAILER. PERSONNEL DONNED PPE AND ENTERED TRAILER TO FIND A DRUM HAD BEGUN TO LEAK AT THE TOP RING. DRUM WAS DAMAGED; AT LEAK AREA, A SECTION OF THE RING WAS SMASHED HORIZONTALLY AND DENTED VERTICALLY AT AN INTERSECTION POINT. THE SUBSTANCE HAD SEEPED THRU THE FLOORBOARDS OF THE LEASE TRAILER AFTER ABSORBING MUCH OF THE MATERIAL. DRUM WAS OVERPACKED; FLOOR-DRY APPLIED TO THE FLOOR AND SWEPT UP AND PLACED INSIDE A 55-GALLON DRUM. A SECTION OF THE GOUND APPROXIMATELY 15'X8'X8' WAS REMOVED AND PLACED INTO THE ABOVE AND SUBSEQUENTLY ONE MORE 55-GAL. DRUM. DRUMS WERE THEN PLACED BACK INTO THE TRAILER TO BE DELIVERED WITH THE ORIGINAL LOAD FOR DISPOSAL. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DISPOSAL FACILITY AND OFF-LOADED; TRAILER WILL BE CLEANED AND DECONTAMINATED. AT WHICH TIME, FLOOR AREA WILL BE ASSESSED FOR REMAINING CONTAMINATION AS APPLICABLE FOR SAFETY & APPEARANCE REASONS AND DETERMINED IF REMOVAL/REPLACEMENT IS WARRANTED.
DRIVER OPENED VALVES TO START PUMP-FITTING STARTED TO LEAK. CLOSED VALVES AND REPLACED FITTING. PLASTIC FITTING WAS REPLACED WITH 307 S.S.

SPILL OCCURRED DUE TO A VALVE NOT BEING CLOSED INTO A TANK OTHER THAN THE ONE WE WERE UNLOADING INTO. SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO NEBRASKA D.E.Q. INSTRUCTIONS.

WHEN THE ROLL-OFF BOX WAS LOADED, THE MATERIAL (GREASE AND DEBRIS) WAS SOLID. DUE TO EXTREMELY HOT TEMPERATURES (THE OUTDOOR TEMPERATURE WAS APPROXIMATELY 96 DEGREES, SO THE ROLL-OFF BOX EXCEEDED 100 DEGREES F) THE MATERIAL BECAME MORE FLOWABLE. DUE TO THE FACT THE MATERIAL WAS MORE FLOWABLE, WE BELIEVE SOME SPLASHING OCCURRED. WE ALSO BELIEVE THE DOOR MAY NOT HAVE SEALED PROPERLY. THESE ARE THE PROBLEMS WE HAVE DETECTED THAT CAUSED THE SPILLAGE. AS SOON AS WE WERE NOTIFIED, A CLEAN-UP CREW WAS DISPATCHED. ALL MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP FROM THE GROUND AND PLACED IN THE ROLL-OFF BOX. THE ROLL-OFF BOX ITSELF WAS CLEANED. ACTION TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS IS TO VERIFY THE SEALING OF EACH BOX AND CONSIDER THE POSSIBILITY OF THE MATERIAL BEING AFFECTED BY HEAT.

column168: ON AUG 19, 1994, DELIVERING 241.3 GALLONS TO 723 E MARKET ST, DANVILLE, PA, TO 550 GALLONS OF STORAGE. I STARTED TO MAKE DELIVERY BUT WHISTLE WAS NOT VERY LOUD. I FIGURED AIR FLOW WAS RESTRICTED BECAUSE IT WAS AN OPEN VENTPIPE (NO CAP/SCREEN - JUST NA ELBOW POINTED DOWN TOWARD SIDEWALK). I GOT ON MY KNEES TO HEAR BETTER AND SEE IF I COULD FREE VENT OF ANY OBSTRUCTION, WHEN WHISTLE STOPPED AND PRODUCT CAME OUT THE VENT PIPE ONTO SIDEWALK (APPROX 2 GAL). I STOPPED DELIVERY AND CONTAINED SPILL TO A PUDDLE ON THE SIDEWALK AND RADIO'D PERRY FOR HELP. UPON HIS ARRIVAL, WE THOROUGHLY CLEANED UP SPILL ON SIDEWALK AND REMOVED FROM MR. CARR'S PROPERTY. MR CARR'S TANKS IN BASEMENT HAD WEEPED APPROX 1 QT OF OIL FROM GUAGE GLASS TOP ONTO TANK AND BASEMENT FLOOR. GAUGE WAS BROKEN AND STUCK ON EMPTY. OIL WAS CLENAED UP AND REMOVED FROM MR CARR'S PROPERTY. PERRY EXPLAINED TO MR CARR THAT VENT PIPE WAS TOO SMALL AND NOT PIPED PROPERLY EITHER. THE VENTPIPE WAS LOWER THAN THE FILL PIPE. PERRY INDICATED THAT IT SHOULD BE CORRECTED TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER SPILL AND MR CARR AGREED.

WHEN FREIGHT ARRIVED MMT THERE WAS 1 EMPTY GALLON JUG IN THE BOX OF 4 JUGS. THERE WAS NO RESIDUE IN TRLR APPARENTLY THE SPILLED LIQUID HAD EVAPORATED ENROUTE TO MMT. THE CARDBOARD BOX WAS RECOUPED AND SENT ON TO CONSIGNEE.

I WAS TOLD THAT THERE WAS A PROBLEM AT 169 DOOR. WHEN I GOT TO THE DOOR I SAW MATERIAL LEAKING OUT. SAND WAS PUT DOWN AROUND UNIT TO CONTAIN SPILL. CALLED CHEMTREC AND COLUMBUS FIRE DEPT. MESI INC HANDLED THE CLEANUP AND WILL HANDLE THE WASTE DISPOSAL FOR CF. THIS INCIDENT IS UNDER INVESTIGATION.

HAWKINS CHEMICAL WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO FSI ON AUGUST 10, 1995 AT 11:00AMWHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED A LIQUID SOLUTION DRIPPING FROM A TRAILER. THE DRIVERENTERED THE TRAILER AND DETRMINED THE SOLUTION DRIPPING FROM A TRAILER. THEDRIVER ENTERED THE TRAILER AND DETERMINED THE SOLUTION TO BE SULFURIC ACID THATWAS LEAKING FROM A 55 GALLON POLY DRUM. A 181/Y1.8 DRUM, NET WEIGHT OF 750#.THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY APPLIED SODA ASH AND FLOOR DRY TO CONTAIN THE SPILL INTHE TRAILER. HE NOTIFIED FSI PERSONNEL AND CALLED TOM DELLICH AT HAWKINSCHEMICAL INC. HAWKINS CHEMICAL DISPATCHED A TRUCK AND TWO (2) MEN TO FSI WITHSODA ASH TO FURTHER HELP CONTAIN THE SPILL. FSI CALLED THE LOCAL FIREDEPARTMENT, THE EPA AND THE CARVER COUNTY ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENT. THE FSIRESPONSE TEAM TOOK CONTROL OF THE SITUATION UNTIL THE HAWKINS CHEMCIAL TRUCKAND TOM DELLICH ARRIVED. AT THE TIME ADDITIONAL SODA ASH WAS APPLIED ON THEGROUND ON THE BLACK TOP, IN THE HAWKINS CHEMICAL TRAILER AND ON THE DRUM. THELEAKING DRUM WAS TRASFERRE TO A OVER-PACK POLY DRUM AND REMOVED FROM THE SITEBY HAWKINS CHEMICAL TRUCK. THE SODA ASH THAT WAS USED TO COVER THE ACID ON THEGROUND WAS SWEPT UP AND PUT INTO POYL DRUMS AND REMOVED FROM THE SITE ON AHAWKINS CHEMICAL TRUCK. THE SODA ASH WAS BROUGHT BACK TO HAWKINS CHEMICAL FORNEUTRALIZATION. THE SODA ASH HAD A PH OF 9. ALL THE SODA ASH WAS USED FORNEUTRALIZATION. THE LEAKING SULFURIC ACID WAS REPACKAGED INTO FIVE (5) GALLONCONTAINERS AT HAWKINS CHEMICAL.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1300 ON 8/23/95 N & M TRANSFER DRIVER ARLYN WESTPAL NOTIFIED HIS DISPATCHER ABOUT A SPILL THAT HAD JUST OCCURRED IN HIS TRAILER.  THE DISPATCHER THEN FORWARDED THE CALL TO THE N & M SAFETY OFFICE.  THE DRIVER REPORTED THAT HE HAD (2) SIX FOOT CYLINDRICAL POLYETHYLENE PORTABLE TANKS THAT WERE LOADED ON HIS TRAILER.  BOTH TANKS HAD BEEN LOADED ON SKIDS.  APPARENTLY WHEN THE N & M DRIVER APPLIED HIS BRAKES ONE OF THE TWO TANKS SLID FORWARD AND TIPPED OVER OFF THE SKID. BECAUSE THE TANKS WERE ELEVATED ON SKIDS, AND BECAUSE THE FREIGHT LOADED IN FRONT OF THE TANKS WAS SO LOW, ONE OF THE TWO TANKS TOPPLED OVER. LEAKAGE OF APPROXIMATELY (5) GALLONS OCCURRED THROUGH THE TOP OF THE TANK. OIL DRY WAS IMMEDIATELY SPREAD OVER THE AREA OF THE TRAILER FLOOR THAT WAS EXPOSED TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  NONE OF THE HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION HIT THE GROUND.  THE N & M TRANSFER DOCKMAN RESPONSIBLE FOR THE LOADING WILL RECEIVE A WRITTEN NOTICE OF WARNING FOR "FAILING TO PROPERLY SECURE A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTAINER."  THE N & M TRANSFER TRAILER EXPOSED TO THE SPILL CONTENTS WAS TAKEN TO A LOCAL TANK WASH / TREATMENT FACILITY FOR DECONTAMINATION.  ( SEE ATTACHED PHOTOCOPY OF PHOTO TAKEN AT THE TIME OF DELIVERY).

AN EMPLOYEE AWARENESS INTERVIEW WAS PUT IN JEFFS FILE AND HE RECD 3 DAY LAY OFF.  PROPER HANDLING PROCEDURES OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WILL BE DISCUSSED IN NEXT DOCK MEETING. I INITIATED AN EMERGENCY DESCENT AND LANDED AT R & R LODGE. ON DESCENT I COMMUNICATED WITH THE LODGE AND RELAYED MY SITUATION TO THEM. INCIDENT WAS CAUSED DUE TO 3 PRIMARY REASONS: 1. ONE WAY LEASE TRAILER WITH ROLL TOP DOOR WAS USED ON THE RAIL 2. VERY POOR LOAD - NO BLOCKING, BRACING, DUNNAGE OR AIRBAGS USED. 3. TRAILER WAS "HUMPED" CAUSING LOAD TO SHIFT TOWARDS THE BACK DOOR. THIS TRAILER WAS LOADED FROM POP TO DLS (XTRL-9712). THE REAR DOOR OF THE TRAILER WAS BROKEN OUT WHILE IN TRANSIT ON THE RAILCAR, CAUSING FREIGHT TO SPILL OUT OF AND ALONG RAILCARS AND TRACKS. THE TRAILER WAS TAKEN OFF THE RAIL AT COLUMBUS. SOME FREIGHT WAS WORKED IT WAS WORKED AND LOADED ONTO OTHER TRAILERS. ONE DRUM WAS LOST AND NOT RECOVERED. IT'S BELIEVED TO HAVE BEEN TOTALLY DESTROYED BY THE TRAIN. THE SECOND DRUM WAS PLACED IN A "OVER-PACK" CONTAINER TO BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. PICTURES ON FILE.

THE DOORS OF THE TRAILER WERE CLOSED AND A PLAN WAS DEVELOPED WITH THE SHIPPER ON HOW TO RECOUP THE SPILLED MATERIAL. THE TORN BAGS WERE TAPED AND PLASTIC WRAPPED AND THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP USING BROOMS AND SHOVEL. THE SPILLED PRODUCT WILL BE DISPOSED OF VIA OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WASTE CONTRACTOR. THE FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS PROVIDED INDIVIDUAL INSTRUCTION ON PROPER METHODS OF HANDLING FREIGHT AND GIVEN A WRITTEN PROGRESSIVE DISCIPLINE WARNING.

DRIVER HAD RETURNED TO TERMINAL AFTER MAKING PICK-UP & UN-LOADED 3 PAILS. WHEN HE PICKED ONE OF THE PAILS UP TO LOAD IT ON ANOTHER TRAILER, HE NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID ON THE DOCK FLOOR. HE THEN NOTIFIED A SUPERVISOR AND THE PAIL WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED OF A POSSIBLE HAZMAT SPILL ON AUGUST 10, 1995 AT 0455L. ONE DRUM OF UN1197 WAS CRUSHED BY A FORKLIFT. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED IN THE DISPOSAL AREA AWAITING DISPOSITION BY THE ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPT.

DOCK WORKER WAS LOADING 33 DOOR (KOKOMO, IND.) FREIGHT INVOLVED CONSISTED OF 4 BARRELS SHRINK WRAPPED ON 1 SKID. WHEN FREIGHT WAS LOADED ON THE SKID TRAILER, IT CAUGHT ON SKID LOADED ON THE RIGHT. THE FRONT BARREL ON THE SKID RECEIVED A TEAR AT THIS TIME. FREIGHT WAS REMOVED TO DOCK, BARREL WAS ROLLED ON SIDE TO STOP LEAK. AREA WAS ISOLATED AND AN OUTSIDE SPILL RECOVERY CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED IN TO CLEAN UP AREA INVOLVED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: OIL-DRI TRANSPORTATION DRIVER PICKED UP LOADED/SCALED LTL LOAD FROM ORIGIN CARRIER NORTH BERGEN, NJ. DRIVER'S LAST STOP BEFORE DISCOVERY OF LEAK WAS IN MIDWAY, GA (OFF I-95) WHERE DRIVER TOOK AN 8 HOUR BREAK. OIL-DRI DRIVER DID A POST TRIP PRIOR TO GOING INTO THE SLEEPERAND A PRE-TRIP BEFORE CONTINUING ON TRIP AND THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF A LEAK. OIL-DRI DRIVER PULLED INTOSCALE 16-B (OFF I-95) IN YULEE, FL (DISTANCE OF 78 MILES FROM MIDWAY, GA)  WHERE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED. YULEE, FL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND FLORIDA DOT RESPONDED TO SPILL. OIL-DRI TRANSPORTATION UNIT WAS PLACED OUT OF SERVICE BY OFFICER R.D. BLANTON OF THE FLORIDA DOT FOR HAZ MAT LEAK AND DRUM NOT PROPERLY BLOCKED OR BRACED. CHEM-TREC WAS CONTACTED AND FLORIDA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WAS CONTACTED. AMERICAN COMPLIANCE TECHNOLOGIES, INC. WAS CONTACTED TO CLEAN UP SPILL. LEAKING DRUM WAS REPACKED (OVER PACK) BY ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDEATION SERVICES, INC. AND UPON COMPLETION OF REPACK, DRIVER AND UNIT WERE ALLOWED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION (TAMPA, FL). AT TAMPA, FL.,AMERICAN COMPLIANCE TECHNOLOGIES, INC. EXAMINED THE TRAILER AND OVERPACK. THE TRAILER WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ON AFTER INSPECTION AND THE REPACKED DRUM WAS REMOVED BY AMERICAN COMPLIANCE TECHNOLOGIES, INC. AND READIED FOR RETURN SHIPMENT TO ORIGINAL SHIPPER (SALVENTS AND PETROLEUM SERVICES OF SYRACUSE, NY.).

THE RELEASED CHEMICAL WAS FULLY CONTAINED AND RAN INTO THE SITE'S SPILL DRAIN WHICH CAPTURES ANY RELEASED CHEMICAL. THE DISCHARGE ADAPTOR PLATE LINING FAILED WHICH CAUSED THE LOCATION TO CORRODE AND RUPTURE. THE ADAPTOR WAS REPLACED.

THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED BACK INTO SERVICE AT THAT TIME. THE SMALL AMOUNT RELEASED ON THE OUTSIDE SHELL OF THE TANK CAR WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AS WAS A SMALL AMOUNT ON THE GROUND.

AND THE ARIZONA CORPORATION COMMISSION HAZ MAT INSPECTOR WERE SOUGHT.  AN ATTEMPT TO COOL THE CAR AND RESEAT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS UNSUCCESSFUL.  AS THE VALVE WAS CONSIDERED DEFECTIVE OR FROZEN OPEN. A FIREMAN USED A SPARKLESS HAMMER TO STRIKE THE VALVE.  THIS ACTION RESULTED IN CLOSING THE VALVE.  THE CAR WAS SPOTTED TO A LOCAL INDUSTRY WHERE APPROXIMATELY 700 GALLONS OR PRODUCT WAS REMOVED AS A PRECAUTION.  CAR WAS FORWARDED FOR UNLOADING, THEN CONSIGNED TO A REPAIR FACILITY FOR EVALUATION.  YARD OPERATIONS WERE SUSPENDED FOR APPROXIMATELY 1 1/2 HOURS.  AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE DURING COOLING.

SHIPPER'S CONTRACTOR LOCATED SOURCE OF RELEASE TO BE ONE POLY DRUM NEAR REAR OF LOAD SIX DRUMS WERE SURROUND BY FIBERBOARD BOXES (ALL ON LOWER LEVEL).  A PALLETIZED LOAD OF BOXES IN THE SECOND LAYER FELL ONTO FLOOR LAYER ACCOUNT LACK OF BLOCKING AND BRACING.  THE PALLET STRUCK ONE DRUM, CRUSHING ITS SIDE WALLS AND CAUSING THE LEAK. TRAILER WAS CLEANED AND RELEASED FOR LOCAL DELIVERY.

THIS DIRT WAS TO THE EDGE OF THE PARKING LOT:  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK.  ALL SPILL MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN A STILL DRUM FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column168: THE BOX WAS DISCOVERED ON DOCK.  IT WAS LEAKING AND WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM IN OS&D.

DRUM WAS LEAKING AROUND THE BOTTOM WHEN UNLOADED.  THERE WAS A SMALL HOLE IN THE BOTTOM.  IT LOOKED LIKE THE DRUM DOLLY HAD PUNCTURED THE DRUM. CLEANED UP THE SPILL, STOPPED THE LEAK, AND PLACED THE DRUM IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BAY.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND MOVED ON TO DESTINATION.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR DELIVERY AT HIS DESTINATION.  WHEN HE WAS IN THE PROCESS OF HOOKING UP TO UNLOAD HE NOTED THAT THE UNLOADING HOSE WAS DEFECTIVE.  HE TOLD THE RECEIVER THAT HE WOULD HAVE TO OBTAIN ANOTHER HOSE AND THE RECEIVER PROVIDED ONE.  IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSFERRING THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE OUR DRIVER NOTED THAT THE HOSE STARTED TO SWELL.  HE SHUT DOWN AND NOTIFIED THE RECEIVER WHO SAID THAT HE FELT THE HOSE WOULD NOT FAIL.  OUR DRIVER PROCEEDED TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE AND A FEW MINUTES LATER THE HOSE FAILED.  OUR DRIVER SHUT DOWN IMMEDIATELY AND TH SPILL AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY THE CUSTOMER.  THE DRIVER OBTAINED ANOTHER HOSE FROM A VENDOR AND COMPLETED HIS DELIVERY.
CUSTOMER HAD A LEAK INSIDE TANK DAM & WHEN DRIVER STARTED TO UNLOAD PRODUCT DRIPPED OUT.  PRODUCT WENT INTO A CONTAINMENT AREA.

PACKING AND PUMP WENT OUT AND PRODUCT SPRAYED OUT.  MOST WAS CAUGHT IN BUCKET.  SOME SPRAYED AN GRAVEE CUSTOMER CLEANED UP.
PRODUCT LOADED INTO TRAILER - TRAILER LEAKING PRODUCT TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER PRODUCT CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBANT.
LEAK DEVELOPED FROM THE O-RING ON PUMP.  CUSTOMER CLEANED UP SPILL.
DRIVER UNLOADING CAUGHT PRODUCT IN BUCKET AND THE BUCKET WAS LEAKING.  HAD A VERY SMALL PIN HOLE.  PRODUCT CLEANED UP WITH SOAP AND WATER.

CONTAINED DRIP WITH BUCKET AND NOTIFIED SAFETY DEPT.  ANOTHER TANK WAS SENT TO TRANSFER PRODUCT OVER.  DRIVER WEIGHTED SECOND UNIT BUT NO DIFFERENCE IN WEIGHT.

AT FIRST POINT OF UNLOADING, NO LEAKAGE WAS DETECTED, HOWEVER, AT CUSTOMERS DOCK IT WAS NOTICED THAT THERE WAS PRODUCT ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  DUE TO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, ALND ODOR, HAZ MAT CLEAN UP COMPANY WAS CALLED.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBANT AND PLACED IN OVERPACK WHICH HAZ MAT COMPANY DISPOSAL OF PROPERLY.  PRODUCT NEVER LEFT THE CONFINES OF OUR TRAILER.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH NOT LESS THAN 20 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 40 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING DRUM WITH A DRUM CART.  THE DRUM APPARENTLY WAS NOT ON THE CART COMPLETELY STRAIGHT AS IT SLID OFF OF THE TIPS AND PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO TEXTILE CHEMICAL.  THE AMOUNT LOST WAS LESS THAN 1 GALLON AND WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBANTS AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM PHELPS DODGE MAGNET WIRE CO.  LOCATED AT PO BOX 1226 IN LAURINBURG, NC TO SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS STOPPAGE LOCATION LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE WHERE IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM A PINHOLE LEAK IN THE SIDE OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER INDICATED THAT A PINHOLE LEAK HAD DEVELOPED AT THE SITE OF A DENT THAT APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY A FORK-LIFT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL CLEAN UP DEBRIS WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING PAPER.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

A SEA CONTAINER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM THE ROYAL BANK OF CANADA LOCATED AT LOS FRAILES IND AL(INTERIOR) IN GUAYNABO, PR TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT, INC. LOCATED AT 51 BRODERICK ROAD IN BRISTOL CT. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SEAGIRT MARINE TERMINAL IN BALTIMORE MD, THE SEA CONTAINER WAS PLACED ON A CHASSIS PENDING CONTINUING TRANSPORT.  AN INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER BY A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF THE ENVIRONMENT IDENTIFIED THAT APPROXIMATELY 4 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME OF ONE OF THE CONTIANEERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE DECISION WAS MADE TO OVERPACK THE CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM AND THIS WAS ACCOMPLISHED AT THE SCENE.  ALL CLEAN UP DEBRIS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THIS RELEASE WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORT TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER INDICATED THAT THE PROBABLE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS A REDUCTION IN THE STRUCTURAL INTEGRITY OF THE DRUM.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, LOADING PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO OVERPACK ANY CONTAINER THAT IS FOUND TO BE NOT STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A BULK DELIVERY OF KEROSENE TO THE ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANKS AT A FUEL DELIVERY COMPANY.  OUR DRIVER WAS PUMPING THE LOAD OFF WHEN THE VIBRATION FROM THE PUMP ON OUR TRACTOR CAUSED ONE OF THE LOCKING EARS ON THE PUMP-OFF HOSE TO COME LOOSE.  THE PUMP-OFF HOSE POPPED OFF SPILLING ABOUT 25 GALLONS OF KEROSENE ONTO THE CEMENT AREA UNDER THE TRACTOR AS WELL AS INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA AROUND THE ABOVE GROUND TANK. THE NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND ASSIGNED A REFERENCE  #95-06576 TO THE INCIDENT.  THE AREA WAS CLEANED BY KLEEN-RESOURCCES, INC. OF CLARKSVILLE, NEW YORK.

column168: OUR LOGEX DRIVER WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON HIGHWAY 60, HIGHWAY 60 IS A ROAD THAT GOES THROUGH AN AREA KNOWN AS SALT RIVER CANYON.  IT IS A ROAD THAT HAS MANY TWISTS AND TURNS AND GOES UP AND DOWN STEEP GRADES.  THE DRIVER WAS COMING DOWN A STEEP GRADE AND FOUND THAT HIS BRAKES BEGAN TO FADE.  HE WAS UNABLE TO NEGOTIATE A SHARP CURVE AND ROLLED OVER.  UPON INVESTIGATION, WE FEEL THAT THE CONSTANT BRAKING HAD WARMED THE BRAKES UP AND WHEN THE DRIVER APPLIED THEM FOR THE LAST GRADE, THEY COULDN'T HOLD. THE BRAKES WERE CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE FINE, AIR TANKS STILL HAD 75 POUNDS OF PRESSURE.

column168: A TRACK SUPERVISOR INSPECTING THE MAIN TRACK REPORTED A STENCH AS HE PASSED IN THE VICINITY OF THE TANK CAR.  THE CAR HAD BEEN PLACED ON THE INTERCHANGE TRACK BY A SOUTHERN PACIFIC LOCAL CREW.  THE CALDWELL FIRE DEPARTMENT APPLIED WATER TO THE CAR IN AN ATTEMPT TO COOL THE PRODUCT. THE AMBIENT TEMPERATURE WAS IN TEH LOW 90S WITH A SOUTHWESTERLY WIND IN THE 10 TO 15 MPH RANGE.  ATSF RESPONDERS MADE AN ASSESSMENT OF THE CAR'S CONDITION, CLOSURES AND VALVES AND TOOK NO EXCEPTIONS.  THE SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVE AND THE RESPONDERS CONVERSED BY PHONE CONCERNING INSPECTION LOCATIONS AND POSSIBLE SOURCES OF THE EARLIER RELEASE.  THE MOST LIKELY CAUSE OF THE DETECTED ODOR WAS DECIDED TO BE A VENTING OF PRODUCT, LIKELY THROUGH THE SAFETY VALVE.  THERE WAS NOT ANY INDICATION OF PRODUCT AT ANY LOCATION ON THE CAR, AND THERE WERE NO FURTHER RELEASES DETECTED AFTER THE INITIAL REPORT.  THE REPORTED INJURIES INVOLVED AN ADJACENT PROPERTY OWNERE AND FAMILY.  THREE MEMBERS OF THE FAMILY WERE TREATED AND RELEASED; HOWEVER, ONE ADDITIONAL ADULT WAS HOSPITALIZED FOR TREATMENT LATER THAT EVENING. THE HOME WAS DOWNWIND OF THE INVOLVED TRACK.  THE ONE PERSON REPORTED AS EVACUATED WAS A RESIDENT OF THIS HOME.

ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTIANER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE NOT STRUCTURALLY SOUND. THE SKID WAS MOVED TO AN AREA TO VENTILATE AND THE CARTONS WERE UNLOADED UNTIL THE LEAKING CARTON WAS FOUND. ONE CARTON WAS FOUND PUNCTURED BY A NAIL FROM THE SKID. THE PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH STAY DRY AND THE CARTON PLACED INTO A RECOVERY PAIL, MARKED, LABELED,A ND FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS, IT WAS NOTICED THAT ONE 5 GALLON PAIL WAS LEAKING DUE TO THE PAIL COLLAPSING FROM HEAVY FREIGHT BEING LOADED ON TOP. THE PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBANT MATERIAL AND THE PAIL WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED BEFORE FORWARDING TO DESTINATION.  AN IMPROPER LOADING REPORT WILL BE COMPLETED IN ORDER TO PREVENT INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE IN THE FUTURE.
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS, ONE CARTON WAS DAMAGED BY THE FORKLIFT BLADE.  THE PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBANT MATERIAL, WAS PLACED IN THE HAZMAT BAY. WE ARE AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER AT THE PRESENT TIME.  PROPER HANDLING PROCEDURES WILL BE COVERED WITH THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR IN ORDER TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE.

WHILE A ROUTINE HUMPING OPERATION WAS BEING CONDUCTED, ACFX 71100 WAS OVER IMPACTED RUPTURING THE FRANGIBLE DISC ON THE SAFETY VENT. CAR WAS ISOLATED AND FRANGIBLE DISC WAS REPLACED.  CARRIER EXERCISED UNREASONABLE USE OF THE ROLLING STOCK.  THE CAR CONTINUED ENROUTE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT ON SIDE OF DRUMS AT HIS 2ND STOP.  DRIVER CHECKED THE TWO DRUMS WHICH WERE LEAKING AND NOTICED THAT ONE DRUM DID NOT HAVE GASKET IN THE LID AND DRUM #2 GASKET WAS IN POOR CONDITION.  DRIVER APPLIED THICK BEAD OF SILICONE AROUND DRUM LIDS IN PLACE OF GASKET. AT STOP #3, GENERATOR GAVE DRIVER TWO NEW GASKETS AND THEY WERE APPLIED AT THAT TIME.  NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED OUTSIDE OF TRAILER.

UPON INSPECTION BY ILLINOIS DOT OFFICIALS, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE DRUM WAS LEAKING.  THE TRUCK WAS ESCORTED TO A CARTAGE COMPANY WHERE THE SHIPMENT WAS OFFLOADED.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CAUSED BY AN IMPROPERLY SEATED GASKET AROUND THE CLOSURE.  THE DRIVER HAD INSPECTED EACH DRUM AT TIME OF LOADING AND ALL CONTAINERS APPEARED TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION PRIOR TO SHIPMENT.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS OVERPACKED.  NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED OUTSIDE THE TRAILER AS IT WAS CONTAINED ON STEEL SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAN. LOAD PROCEEDED ON TO DESTINATION WITH NO FURTHER PROBLEMS.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: CARGO TANK WAS DROPPED OFF AT VAN WATERS & ROGERS ON 08/17/95 TO BE LOADED. UPON ARRIVING THE NEXT MORNING VAN WATERS NOTICED THE LEAK AND REALEASE. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A VALVE THAT HAD CRACKED INTERNALLY AT THE REAR OF THE TANKER. THE RELEASE WAS CLEANED UP BY VAN WATERS & ROGERS.

ONE CARDBOARD CARTON/CONTAINING 4-1 GALLON GLASS JUGS ARRIVED DAMAGED. THE CONTENTS OF ONE GALLON JUG WAS COMPLETELY LOST DUE TO THE JUG BEING BROKEN.  THE PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED INTO THE CARTON AND THE REMAINING LIQUID WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT.  THE ABSORBENT AND BROKEN CONTAINER WERE PLACED INTO A 15 GALLON OVERPACK AND PLACED INTO OS&D.  THE THREE REMAINING GLASS BOTTLES WERE PLACED INTO A NEW COARDBORAD CARTON, MARKED AND LABELED AND FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINING FREIGHT.  AFTER SURVEYING THE DAMAGE, IT WAS DETERMINED THIS WAS FROM VIBRATION IN TRANSIT.  THIS WAS LOADED APPROXIMATELY INTHE LAST 1/3 OF THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  HEAVY FREIGHT WAS LOADED ON TOP, BUT THEY DO NOT FEEL THIS CONTRIBUTED TO THE LOSS.

DRIVER WAS INSPECTING HIS EQUIPMENT. UPON OPENING DOORS OF TRAILER, HE NOTICED LIQUID PRODUCT IN THE CONTAINMENT PAN IN THE TRAILER. HE NOTIFIED SAFETY AT TSMT.  THE DRIVER WAS ADVISED TO CALL BACK AT 0800 HOURS.  AT THAT TIME, IT WAS DETERMINED A CLEAN UP CREW OVERPACKED LEAKING DRUM AND CLEANED OUT THE TRAILER. ALL OF THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED INSIDE OF THE TRAILER.  THE PENNSYLVANIA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION WAS NOTIFIED ABOUT THIS INCIDENT.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: THIS WAS AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  RAMP AGENT BRUCE STONE DELIVERED A THREE PIECE SHIPMENT TO THE ABQ AND WAS PRESENTING IT TO TIM MCFARLAND.  WHEN STONE GIVE ONE OF THE BOXES TO MCFARLAND HE (MCFARLAND) MADE A COMMENT ABOUT FUMES COMING FROM THE BOX AND SUSPECTED THAT THE MOISTURE ON THE BOX AND THE SMELL WERE THE RESULTS OF LEAKING BATTERY ACID. STONE HAD HELD THE BOX AGAINST HIS UNIFORM AND IMMEDIATELY WENT TO WASH.  WHILE STONE WAS GONE MCFARLAND OPENED THE TOP OF THE CARDBOARD BOX AND FOUND A PLASTIC BATTERY CASE OF THE TYPE SOLD IN AUTO SUPPLY STORES. STONE UNIFORM WAS DAMAGED.

DURING OUTBOUNF TRAIN INSPECTION, CAR INSPECTOR OBSERVED WETNESS AT TOP OFO ACFX 82800.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND SENT PERSONNEL TO INSPECT/SECURE CAR.  MANWAY WAS FOUND TO BE LOOSE.  SHIPPER MADE TEMPORARY REPAIRS AND CAR WAS RETURNED TO POINT OF ORIGIN FOR FURTHER REPAIR.

ACFX 89740 WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED.  A THIRD PARTY REPAIR FIRM RESPONDED AND FOUND THAT A 100# RUPTURE DISK WAS BLOWN.  THE RUPTURE DISK WAS REPLACED AND THE CAR RESECURED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

ACFX 79690 REPORTED LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR NEAR THE "A" END, JUST ABOVE THE TRUCKS.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED. THE SHIPPER'S PERSONNEL FOUND THAT THERE WAS A CORROSION LEAK IN THE TANK SHELL.  UNTIL THE CAR COULD BE MOVED OFFLOADED , CONTAINMENT WAS PLACED UNDERNEATH THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS MOVED BACK TO THE ORIGINATING PLANT (APPROX. 6 MILES) FOR OFFLOADING AND REPAIR.

WHILE SWITCHING CAR IN THE YARD, CREW OBSERVED WETNESS AROUND TOP OF THE CAR.  CAR WAS SET OUT AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED.  SHIPPER'S PERSONNEL FOUND THAT PRODUCT HAD SLOSHED OUT AROUND THE MANWAY.  THE MANWAY WAS RESECURED AND THE SPILLED PRODUCT CLEANED UP OFF CAR.  CAR WAS REINSPECTED AND RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

INSPECTION REVEALED THAT (2) DRUMS HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY NAILS PROTRUDING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX CONTAINER.  THE LEAKING DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED AND THE ENTIRE LOAD WAS RESECURED.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED FOR DISPOSAL.

CAR WAS OBSERVED BY YARD CREW TO BE LEAKING LIQUID FROM A FITTING AT THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED.  THE SHIPPER SENT A REPAIR CREW AND FOUND THAT A GASKET ON THE LIQUID EDUCATION LINE WAS DEFECTIVE.  THE GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

UPON UNLOADING ONE DRUM WAS NICKED AT THE BOTTOM WITH THE HI-LO BLADE.  IT WAS IMMEDIATELY TURNED ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT LEAKING.

ON AUGUST 8, 1995 AROUND 0900 HRS DRIVER AT CONSIGNEE'S.  THE UNIT WAS PLACED ON THE UNLOADING PAD.  AN EMPLOYEE OF THE CONSIGNEE'S REMOVED THE CAP FROM THE EXTERNAL VALVE AND WAS SPLASHED WITH SOME PRODUCT AND LEFT THE AREA PRIOR TO THE DRIVER ARRIVING AT THE BACK OF THE TANK AND VALVE AREA.  IT IS NOT KNOWN IF CONSIGNEE'S EMPLOYEE OPENED THE EXTERNAL AND INTERNAL VALVE OR NOT.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1305 HOURS ON AUGUST 16, 1995, A CONRAIL EMPLOYEE WORKING AT AVON YARD REPORTED TANK CAR CELX23164 VENTING OUT THE TOP OF CAR. OUTSIDE TEMPERATURE WAS 99 DEGREES.  THE TERMPERATURE IN CAR ROSE WHICH CAUSED THE SAFETY VALVE TO VENT.  FIRE DEPARTMENT HOSED DOWN THE CAR TO LOWER PRESSURE WHICH CAUSED VALVE TO RESEAT.  HOWEVER, WHEN THE VALVE RESEATED THE 0 - RING WAS PINCHED CREATING A MINUTE LEAK. CONRAIL TOOK CAR DIRECTLY TO THE CONSIGNEE WHO UNLOADED, DEPRESSURIZED THE CAR AND REPLACED THE SAFETY VALVE.

ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES INC WAS ALSO NOTIFIED AND WERE AT SCENE IMMEDIATELY, MSDS WAS SECURED AND ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES HANDLED IN ACCORDANCE TO MSDS AND PROCEDURE, IT WAS FOUND THAT ONE OF THE CYLINDERS WAS LABELED REJECT FO NOT USE AND APPARENTLY RESIDUE EITHER IN CYLINDER OR ON IT HAD CAUSED THE ODOR DUE TO HOT TEMPERATURES IN TRAILER. CYLINDERS WERE BEING FILLED FOR CONSIGNEE WHEN FOUND DEFECTIVE, CYLINDERS WERE PROPERTY OF MG INDUSTRIES.

column168: DRIVER STATED HE PUT QUICK COUPLER FITTINGS ON THE PUMP BEFORE LEAVING TERMINAL. WHEN HE ARRIVED HE HOOKED UP THE HOSE FROM THE CARGO TANK, THEN TO THE STORAGE TANK. STARTED OFF LOADING AND AFTER 3 OR 4 MINUTES THE UNLOADER CHECKED THE LEVEL IN THE STORAGE TANK AND FOUND IT WAS GOING DOWN. HE TOLD THE DRIVER WHO SHUT OFF HIS PUMP AND VALVES. PRODUCT THEN STARTED TO OVERFLOW THE CARGO TANK ONTO THE BLACKTOP. ABOUT 25 GALLONS WENT INTO A DRAIN AND INTO A DITCH WHICH WHICH HAD WATER IN IT. THE CONSIGNEE PUT DOWN ABSORBENT PADS AND CLEANED OFF RESIDUE FROM WATER AND SOAKED UP PRODUCT FROM BLACKTOP. THEY PUT IT IN AN 85-GALLON OVERPACK DRUM AND WILL DISPOSE OF PROPERLY. THIS SPILL WAS CAUSED BY DRIVER ERROR.

I DISCOVERED THE LEAKING PACKAGE.  THE PACKAGE WAS UPSIDE DOWN AND NO LABELS COULD BE SEEN.  I WAS WEARING GLOVES AND GOOGLES.WHEN I TURNED THE PACKAGE OVER, THROUGH A HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE PACKAGE, LIQUID SPLASHED OUT ONTO MY ARMS.  I THEN SAW THE 5-PART LABEL AND DIAMOND HAZARD LABEL, WHICH WERE ALSO ON THE BOTTOM.  I IMMEDIATELY RAN AND WASHED MY ARMS OFF. I RETURNED, PUT ON ALL PPE AND PROCESSED THE PACKAGE.  LATER, MY ARMS DEVELOPED VERY LARGE RED, ITCHY MARKS (ON MY FOREMARMS).  I WAS TAKEN TO ST. MARKS HOSPITAL AND TREATED FOR ACID BURNS.

USED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET. PUT ON PPE, CHECKED CONTENTS, REWRAPPED PACKAGE AND RETURNED PRODUCT TO THE SHIPPER. THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.
TANK CAR WAS OVERFILLED AS IT WAS BEING LOADED. OPERATOR IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF BLOCK VALVE ON LOADING LINE. OPERATOR INATTENTION DURING THE LOADING PROCESS. HE WAS COUNSELED ABOUT THE INCIDENT.

column168: DRIVER WAS MAKING DELIVERY INTO UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK WHEN HE NOTICED GASOLINE COMING FROM ANOTHER FILL DROP LOCATION.  FILL CAP OF UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK HAD BECOME DISCONNECTED.

WHEN DRIVER PICKED UP TRAILER, HE INSPECTED LOAD.  2 BARRELLS WERE TIPPED ON THEIR SIDE, AND IT WAS APPARENT THAT PRODUCT HAD LEAKED OUT OF 1 BARRELL.  BARRELS WERE SET UP RIGHT, AND BUNG'S CHECKED AND TIGHTENED. LOAD RE-SECURED.  NO PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM TRAILER.  LOAD RE-SECURED. NO PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM TRAILER, AND HAD DRIED.  STAY-DRI WAS PUT ON FLOOR AS A PRE CAUTION.  LOAD DELIVERED, TRAILER WAS WASHED OUT AT TRAILER WASHOUT COMPANY.  IT WAS UNKNOWN HOW BARRELLS HAD TIPPED OVER, POSSIBLITY OCCURED WHILE TRAILER MOVED AROUND SPOTTING LOT.  A WORSE SITUATION WAS PREVENTED BY DRIVER FOLLOWING HIS PROPER PROCEDURES.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: AT APPROX. 1705 HRS., WHILE LEGALLY PARKED IN A SERVICE PLAZA ON I76, OUR UNIT WAS STRUCK BY A VAN TRACTOR TRAILER OPERATED BY SYSTEM FREIGHT, JAMESBURG, NJ.  OUR DRIVER WAS IN THE CAB OF OUR UNIT AT THE TIME. APPARENTLY VAN TRAILER'S DOOR HINGES PUNCTURED THE TANK TRAILER MID BARREL HEIGHT, FRONT LEFT SIDE; IMPACT CAUSED 12 INCH "GASH" IN COMPARTMENT WHICH HELD APPROX.  3400 GALLONS OF GASOLINE.  PRODUCT POURED ONTO BLACKTOP AND SOIL.  APPROX. 1336 GALLONS OF PRODUCT LOST TILL PRODUCT LEVEL IN COMPARTMENT REACHED LEVEL OF PUNCTURE.  DRIVER INSTRUCCTED TO NOTIFY SERVICE PLAZA MANAGER AND 911 IMMEDIATELY.  LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT/EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL MANAGED INITIAL RESPONSE AND SERVICE PLAZA EVACUATION.  TWO COMPANY/PA DEPARTMENT OF ENVT.  RESOURCES APPROVED RESPONSE CONTRACTORS RESPONDED TO FIRST, VACCUM LOST PRODUCT, AND SECOND, TO PERFORM REQUIRED REMEDIATION, PER PA DEPT. OF ENVT. RESOURCES REQUIREMENTS.  NO WATERWAYS OR SEWERS WERE IMPACTED NO HIGHWAYS WERE CLOSE DUE TO INCIDENT.  APPROX.  500 GALLONS OF LOST PRODUCT REMOVED AND APPROX. 45 TO 50 TONS OF SOIL REMOVED.

AFTER LOADING, DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE SECURITY CHECK OUT POINT AT 0445 ON 8-30-95.  HE WAS INFORMED THERE WAS PRODUCT LEAKING FROM MY TRAILER.  WHEN I INSPECTED THE TRAILER, HE DETERMINED THE LEAKING WAS CAUSED BY A LOOSE CHRISTMAS TREE VALVE.  HE THEN TIGHTENED THE VALVE AND CLEANED ALL THE PRODUCCT THAT WAS LYING ON THE GROUND.

THERE WERE NO ENVIRONMENTAL CONCERNS OR ANY NEED FOR ASSISTANCE FROM EMERGENCY PEOPLE.

column168: ON THURSDAY AUGUST 17, 1995, THE DRIVER WAS INFORMED THAT THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING. THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL IS AS FOLLOWS:  INTERSTATE 10 REST AREA 14 MILES EAST OF FT STOCKTON TX.  WE DEVELOPED COMMUNICATION WITH THE FT STOCKTON FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT UNIT TO DETERMINE THE SCOPE OF THE WORK. EMERGENCY RESPONSE WORK WAS INITIATED WITH ECO LOGICAL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, MIDLAND, TX. THE INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THAT POINT WAS CONVEYED TO THE TEXAS NATURAL RESOURCE CONSERVATION COMMISSOIN(TNRCC) REGION 7 AND CONTINUALLY UPDATED TO PROJECT CONCLUSION. I RESPONDED TO A LEKAER AT PDZ WEARING MY PPE EQUIPMENT. I DISCOVERED A PKG WITH A 5 PART AND CORROSIVE 8 DIAMOND THAT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING. I USED PH TEST STRIP TO CONFIRM THAT AN ACID AS STATED ON THE 5 PART LABEL WAS LEAKING. THE PH TEST WAS CONFIRMED AS AN ACID. I THEN USED BICARBONATE SODA TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILL. I THEN REMOVED THE PACKAGE AND CLEAN UP MATERIAL AND TOOK THEM TO THE PSC AREA. THE PKG WAS DMP'D REPACKAGED AND RTS. CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.
I RESPONDED TO A LEAKER ON PD 2 WEARING MY PPE ITEMS, THE SPILL CONTAINS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE AND ABSORBED WITH KITTY LITTER. THE REMAINING CONTENTS RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

I RESPONDED TO A LEAKER WEARING THE PROPER PPE. FOUND A BOX MARKED CORROSIVE 8. TESTED LEAK WITH PH TEST STRIP. USED CLAY AND SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE LEAKED MATERIAL. RECOVERED PKG FROM TRACK AND TOOK IT TO PSC AREA. ALL LIQUID WAS ABSORBED AND NEUTRALIZED, PLACED IN PLASTIC BAG ALONG WITH OUTER CORRUGATED CONTAINER AND CLEAN UP OF MATERIALS. WE THEN PROCESSED THE MATERIAL THROUGH DMP. REMAINING CONTENTS WERE RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

RUPTURE DISK WAS REPLACED AND OUTSIDE OF TANK WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH VINEGAR, THEN RINSED WITH WATER WHICH WAS CAUGHT FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: THIS REPORT IS BEING SUBMITTED OUT OF AN ABUNDANCE OF CAUTION. IN RESPONSE TO AN ALLEDGED PRODUCT RELEASE AT A SERVICE STATION, FOR WHICH ARCO, AT THISTIME, DOES NOT ADMIT RESPONSIBILITY.  ARCO'S INVESTIGATION TO DATE HAS NOT BEEN SUCCESSFUL IN DETERMINING EXACTLY WHEN OR HOW THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AND WHO MAY BE RESPONSIBLE.  POLICE NOTICED PRODUCT NEAR THE STATION AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED BUT THE GASOLINE HAD EVAPORATED BEFORE THEY ARRIVED.  NO CLEAN UP WAS REQUIRED.  STAINS AT THE SITE INDICATED THAT THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED ON CONCRETE AT THE TOP CONNECTIONS OF AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK AND DID NOT REACH THE STORM DRAIN.  THE SERVICE STATION HAS REMOTE FILLS AND THE CONNECTIONS AT THE TOP OF THE TANK ARE NOT VISIBLE FROM THE REMOTE FILL LOCATION.  THE SERVICE STATION OWNER SURMISED THAT THE RELEASE MAY HAVE OCCURRED DURING PRODUCT OFF LOADING.  THE DRIVER DELIVERING PRODUCT MAY NOT HAVE HAD CORRECT INFORMATION ABOUT THE INVENTORY IN THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS. THIS SERVICE STATION HAS UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS CONFIGURED IN SUCH A WAY THAT THEY CANNOT BE GAUGED WITH A NORMAL SIZED GAUGE POLE.  THE DRIVERS RELY ON THE SERVICE STATION INVENTORY SYSTEM TO DETERMINE IF A LOAD WILL FIT IN THE TANK.  A BREAKDOWN IN COMMUNICATION BETWEEN THE DRIVER AND THE SERVICE STATION ATTENDENT MAY LIKELY HAVE CAUSED THIS RELEASE.  A NEW FORM AND PROCEDURE HAD BEEN INSTITUTED FOR THIS SERVICE STATION THAT CLEARLY COMMUNICATE TANK INVENTORIES TO PRODUCT DELIVERY DRIVER.  THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RETRAINED ON SAFE UNLOADING PROCEDURES. ADDITIONALLY, THIS RELEASE COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF THE CONNECTIONS ON THE TOP OF THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK HAD FUNCTIONED PROPERLY.  THE SERVICE STATION OWNER WAS INFORMED OF THE PROBLEM AND REQUESTED TO FIX THE

OUR DRIVER HAD MADE A PICKUP AT BIDS WAREHOUSE (L.C.I.) AND ONLY 2-3 BLOCKS AWAY FROM THE SHIPPER WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT SPILLING OUT OF THE DISCHARGE LINE. A LOCAL ENVIRONMENTAL FIRM (SMITH ENVIRONMENTAL TECHNOLOGIES CORPORATION) MADE THE CLEAN UP.

UPON OFFLOADING, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THREE (3) DRUMS WERE LEAKING FROM AROUND THE BUNGS.  THE BUNGS WERE TIGHTENED AND MATERIAL WAS OFFLOADED. WHILE LOADING PRODUCT, THE EXTERNAL VALVE WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED RESULTING IN SPRAYING OF THE PRODUCT.  OUR DRIVER WAS SPRAYED IN HIS EYES. HE WAS THEN TAKEN TO A MEDICAL CLINIC WHERE HE SAW THEIR OAC DOCTOR, WHERE HIS EYES WERE AGAIN FLUSHED.  ANTIBIOTIC CREAM WAS ADMINISTERED AND A PATCH WAS PUT ON.  CHEST X-RAY WERE DONE AND THE RESULTS WERE FOUND TO BE NEGATIVE.  UPON RETURN TO HIS HOME TERMINAL HE WAS EXAMINATED BY A PULMONARY EXPERT.  RESULTS WERE NEGATIVE AND WAS RELEASED TO RETURN TO WORK ON 9-6-95.

column168: OF 19 DRUMS OF A PINT 1 DRUM WAS NOT PALLETIZED AND IT HAD FREFGHT THAT WAS ON PALLETS STACKED ALL OF THE WAY UP TO WITHIN 1 FOOT OF THE CEILING BLOCKED UP TIGHT AGAINT IT THAT LOOKED LIKE IT HAD PUNCTURED THE DRUM WHEN IT WAS LOADED.  OT THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR LOADING THE FREIGHT LOCKING UP AGAINST THE DRUM PUNCTURED THE DRUM WITH THE FORKS ON THE FORKLIFT.  THERE WAS  STRONG ODOR OF PAINT WHEN THE TRAILER WAS BACKED INTO THE UNLOADING DOCK INDICATING THE PUNCTURE OCCURED PRIOR TO DELIVERY.  WHEN THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED THE DRUM WAS TIPPED OVER TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER SPILLAGE.  OIL DRY WAS USED TO ABSORB THE PAINT SPILLED OF APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON. RECOMMENDATION TO AVOID FUTURE INCIDENTS ARE 1) MAKE SURE ALL FREIGHT IS PALLETIZED.  2) DO NOT PRESS ADDITIONAL FREIGHT SO TIGHT AGAINST THE DRUMS. 3) WHEN LOADING OR UNLOADING DO NOT ALLOW THE FORKS OF THE FORKLIFT EXTEN PAST THE FREIGHR THEY AREA LOADING.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON AUGUST 7, 1995, A LEASE OPERATOR WORKING FOR THIS COMPANY WAS INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT ON I64 AT MILE MARKER 23 IN WEST VIRGINIA.  AS A RESULT OF THIS ACCIDENT THERE WAS AN UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS WASTE. THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED AROUND 1:00 PM AND WAS CAUSED WHEN ERIKA TYLER, TRAVELING EAST BOUND, CROSSED THE MEDIAN IN HER AUTOMOBILE AND COLLIDED WITH A TRACTOR-TRAILER DRIVEN BY EIL SNYDER. THE TRUCK FLIPPED ON ITS SIDE, SPILLING ABOUT A TON HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE VEHICLE LANDED ON IT RIGHT SIDE ABOUT 25 FEET FROM THE SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY.  THE DRIVER WAS NOT SERIOUSLY INJURED AND ANOTHER VEHICLE TRAVELING WITH HIM NOTIFIED OUR COMPANY OF THE ACCIDENT/SPILL.  WE IMMEDIATELY BEGAN EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROCEDURES AS PER OUR CONTINGENCY PLAN.  AT 1:40 PM I CONTACTED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER AND NOTIFIED THEM OF THE INCIDENT  FILE #303003. AFTER SPEAKING WITH WEST VIRGINIA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENT, TOM FISHER, I CONTACTED WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP IN CHARLESTON, WEST VIRGINIA.  THEY DISPATCHED MEN AND EQUIPMENT TO BEGIN CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS.  I THEN NOTIFIED THE GENERATOR, ROANOKE COUNTY AND ROANOKE ELECTRIC STEEL.  AT 3:30 PM I DISPATCHED ANOTHER TRACTOR TRAILER TO THE SCENE TO TRANSPORT MATERIAL FROM THE CLEAN-UP.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND THE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER WERE REMOVED FROM THE SITE AND RETURNED TO THE GENERATOR.  CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETE AROUND 11:00PM THAT EVENING.  THE FOLLOWING DAY WEAVERTOWN RETURNED TO THE SITE TO SAMPLE THE AREA.  THE ANALYSIS OF THE SAMPLES SHOWED TWO AREA WHICH NEEDED FURTHER EXCAVATIONS.  ON FRIDAY AUGUST 18, 1995, WEAVERTOWN RETURNED TO THE SITE AND REMOVED THE REMAINING CONTAMINATED.  SOIL SAMPLES TAKEN AFTER EXCAVATION CONFIRMED COMPLETION AND THE REMAINING MATERIAL WAS ALSO TRANSPORTED BACK TO ROANOKE COUNTY.  WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL THEN RETURNED TO THE SITE TO RE-SOD AND RE-SEED THE EXCAVATION SITE. THE SOIL AND WASTE COLLECTED AT THE ACCIDENT/SPILL SITE WAS STABILIZED AND DISPOSED ON SITE AT DIXIE CAVERNS LANDFILL, ROANOKE COUNTY, VIRGINIA, AS PER EPA'S APPROVAL.  ENCLOSED WITH THIS LETTER ARE ALL MANIFESTS, BILLING, SITE DIAGRAMS AND OTHER PERTINENT INFORMATION.  IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS PLEASE CONTACT ME.  JOHN CLINGAMAN

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER CTS, WAS NOTIFIED BY GARY HUNTER, MYO YERMO, CALIFORNIA, THAT SWITCH CREW NOTED A TANK CAR LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR. THE CAR WAS PLACED ON THE CABOOSE TRACK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE TANK CAR, AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT. THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD GATX TRI-VENT, WHICH IS LOCATED OUTSIDE THE CENTER WORK PLATFORM AREA ON THE "A" END OF THE CAR, WAS DISASSEMBLED AND THE BURST DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE 100 POUND BS&B STAINLESS/TEFLON FRANGIBLE DISC. THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLED, AND THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE ALSO INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE.  DURING THE INSPECTION PROCESS, DEVELOPED THIS CAR TO BE UNDER LOAD AND NOT MOVING AS AN EMPTY PER THE WAYBILL INFORMATION. UPON CONTACTING THE SHIPPER, DEVELOPED THE CAR HAD BEEN PULLED IN ERROR PRIOR TO THE CONTENTS BEING OFF LOADED. THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED TO CONTACT THE ST. LOUIS CUSTOMER SERVICE CENTER AND HAVE THE CAR REVERSE ROUTED BACK TO THEIR FACILITY AND CORRECT THE LADING INFORMATION TO SHOW AS UNDER LOAD, RATHER THAN AS A RESIDUE. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSED, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: UNION PACIFIC MOTOR FREIGHT EMPLOYEES NOTED TRAILER LEAKING ON ARRIVAL AT UPRR OMAHA TRAILER RAMP. TRAILER WAS THEN ISOLATED AWAITING INSPECTION/CORRECTIVE ACTION. INSPECTION BY UPRR SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DECHANT DISCLOSED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM NOSE OF TRAILER, BOTH SIDES. DECHANT REMOVED SECURITY BOLT AND SEAL "EEZ & ELR-0430", ALLOWED TRAIELR TO AIR OUT, AND CONDUCTED CURSORY INSPECTION. LOAD WAS FOUND TO CONSIST ENTIRELY OF SMALL CONTAINERS OF ACETONE, TOLUENE, NAPHTHA, AND NUMEROUS FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, ALONG WITH MURIATIC ACID AND LINSEED OIL. THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING OF ANY KIND PRESENT, AND A LARGE LOAD SHIFT WAS APPARENT AT THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER, WHERE A SIX FOOT VOID HAD EXISTED BETWEEN THE WALL OF THE TRAILER AND THE FOREMOST PALLETS IN THE LOAD. ALL OF PART OF TWO PALLETS APPERARED TO HAVE FALLEN, WITH LEAKAGE APPEARING TO EMANATE FROM THIS POINT. THE LOAD REMAINED ISOLATED AWAITING TRANSLOAD. LEAKAGE WAS OF A SUFFICIENTLY SLOW RATE THAT ALL EVAPORATED BEFORE ANY POOLING OR GROUND ABSORPTION OCCURED, AND ALL LEAKED, ALONG WITH NUMEROUS CONTAINERS OF LINSEED OIL, AND OF WHICH HAD BEEN LOADED ON THE PREVIOUSLY MENTIONED FRONT PALLETS. TRAILER WAS EMPTIED, AND ALL LEAKING OR CONTAMINATED CARTONS WERE PLACED IN OVERPACK DRUMS WHILE TRAILER WAS CLEANED FOR PLACEMENT BACK INTO SERVICE. ALL ORIGINAL CONTENTS, INCLUDING OVERPACKED MATERIAL, WERE THEN PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL TRAILER AND FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

column168: SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, VERN LIBBY WAS ADVISED THAT CONTAINER APLU 704252 HAD ARRIVED IN RAMP TRACK 3 AT SEATTLE, WA. AND APPEARED TO BE LEAKING. INVESTIGATION DEVELOPED CONTAINER IN QUESTION TO BE STACKED ON TOP OF CONTAINER TRIU 473054 AND LOADED IN APLX 2136C BOTH REFLECTING SIGNS OF BEING CONTAMINATED. THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION WAS LOWERED TO THE GROUND AND INTERIOR INSPECTION WAS CONDUCTED. NO BLOCKING OR BRACING WAS NOTED. NOTED 14 BLUE PLASTIC 35 GALLON DRUMS LOADED THE 1ST 3RD OF THE CONTAINER SQUEEZED TOGETHER. ONE OF WHICH WAS NOTED WITH THE LOADING BUNG POPPED OUT LYING ON THE DRUM IN QUESTION. ALSO NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM CONTAMINATED 3 OTHERS AND THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER. I CONTACTED THE UNITED WESTERN SUPPLY, SEATTLE (CONSIGNEE) ALICE ANDERSON OFFICE MANAGER, UNITED WESTERN SUPPLY, REQUESTED, WE ISOLATED THE CONTAINERS UNTIL MORNING 08/09. PAT KRAFT, FACILITIES MANAGER AND WALT ROBINS, WAREHOUSE MANAGER, UNITED WESTERN SUPPLY, INSPECTED CONTAINER APLU 704252 AT 0830 HRS. 08/09. IN A JOINT EFFORT THE MISSING BUNG WAS REPLACED. FLOOR DRY WAS PLACED ON TOP OF THE DRUM AND ON THE FLOOR TO CONTROL ANY POSSIBLE FUTURE SPILL. A JOINT AGREEMENT WAS MADE TO DELIVER THE CONTAINER APLU 704252 AS IS, ACCOUNT UNITED WESTERN SUPPLY IS LOCATED WITHIN 2 MILES OF THE UNION PACIFIC MOTOR FREIGHT, SEATTLE. ALICE ANDERSON, OFFICE MANAGER, UNITED WESTERN SUPPLY, CONTACTED JACK MURPHY, ASHLAND CHEMICAL AND ACTING AS ASHLAND REPRESENTATIVE CONTRACTED DIRECTLY WITH FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL TO CLEAN STACKCAR APLX 2136C, CONTAINER TRIU 473054 AND THE INTERIOR OF CONTAINER APLU 704252 WHEN UNLOADING HAS BEEN COMPLETED. BOTH STACKCAR APLX 2136C AND CONTAINER TRIYU 473054 WERE CLEANED AND RELEASED THE AFERNOON OF 08/09/95 BY FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT OGDEN UT. MGR. H.W. RODABOUGH INSPECTED TANKCAR PVCX13526, LOADED CAR SULFURIC ACID. NOTED LEAKING CONDITION ON THE CAR, AROUND THE FILL HOLE. column172: Rail hopper car for solid materials only

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1545 HRS 08/29/95, UNION PACIFIC TRAINMAN, WHILE PREPARING TO COUPLE INTO A TANK CAR, WAS OVERCOME BY AMMONIA VAPORS; HE WAS SUBSEQUENTLY TRANSPORTED TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL, TREATED, AND RELEASED. LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL WERE AMONG THE FIRST TO ARRIVE ON SCENE, HEARD THE SOUND OF ESCAPING VAPORS, AND OBSERVED VAPORS NEAR THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  THEIR SUBSEQUENT INSPECTION DISCLOSED LEAK WAS EMANATING FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE; HOWEVER, IT SUBSIDED COMPLETELY PRIOR TO THEM TAKING ANY ACTION.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES ARRIVED ON SCENE AND CONDUCTED AN INSPECTION FO THE TANK CAR, AND DETERMINED THE CARUS OF THE LEAK TO BE DEFECTIVE "O" RING(S) ON THE RELIEF VALVE.  THEY DETERMINED THAT THE CAR WAS 5000 LBS BELOW LOADING CAPACITY, WITH INTERNAL PRESSURE WITHIN NORMAL LIMITS.  AMBIENT TEMPERATURE WAS APPROXIMATELY 96-98 DEGREES.  FOLLOW UP INSPECTION BY UPRR SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS KEN DECHANT AND FRA INSPECTOR CRAIG BAGSTAD DISCLOSED NO EVIDENCE OF CONTINUED LEAKAGE.  CAR WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER'S FACILITY FOR OFF LOADING, DEPRESSURIZATIONS, AND REPAIR, IN ACCORDANCE WITH 49 CFR.

UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD PERSONNEL AT ALEXANDRIA, LOUISIANA DECTECTED A SLIGHT ODOR OF AMMONIA COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT AND ISOLATED WITHOUT INCIDENT. UPRR SPECIAL AGENT B G BAREFIELD WAS NOTIFIED AND CALLED UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER.  CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY TM ROBINSON. ROBINSON RESPONDED AND INSPECTED THE CAR.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF VAPOR WAS DETECTED COMING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  A 0 TO 600 PSIG PRESSURE GAUGE WAS USED AND REGISTERED ZERO NEEDLE DEFLECTION.  ROBINSON TELEPHONED MR. BOB BROWNING OF FARMLAND IND. AT THE NEAR BY PLANT.  IT WAS AGREED THAT THE PROBLEM WAS DEFECTIVE "O" RINGS IN THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AND THAT THE CAR WOULD BE SPOTTED INTO THE PLANT FOR COMPLETE DEPRESSURIZATION AND REPAIR.  THIS MOVE WAS COMPLETED ON THE MORNING OF TUESDAY, 08/29/95, WITHOUT INCIDENT.

REMOVAL AND INSPECTION OF UNION TANKCAR 2 1/2 VACUUM RELIEF VALVE REVEALED THAT THE O RING WAS DEFECTIVE AND CAUSE OF RELEASE. MGR LERCH REPLACED VALVE WITH A 2 1/2 PLUG WHICH STOPPED RELEASE AND SECURED CAR. REGIONAL MANAGER RM STINE WAS CONTACTED BY MYO JOHN LUTGEN ADVISING THE ENGINEER WORKING THE HUMP JOB REPORTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF CAR NATX 38503.  CAR BEING A LOAD OF ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGE, MOVING IN BOND THE FOLLOWING SEALS WERE RECORDED; BOTTOM OUTLET "MIDWEST 203211" ALSO A CABLE 203210".  THIS SEAL WAS REMOVED FOR INSPECTION WHICH DEVELOPED THE LEAK WAS AT THE THREADED JOINT WHERE VALVE ATTACHES TO THE 3 INCH LIQUID LINE. NOTED HEAVY PAINT COVERING THE THREADED AREA ON THE LIQUID LINE. THE HEAT OF THE DAY WAS CAUSING A SLIGHT INTERNAL PRESSURE WHICH ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO ESCAPE PAST THE THREADS WITH A WIRE BRUSH AND TIGHTENED THE VALVE THREE COMPLETE TURNS SECURING THE VALVE, THEN RELEASED FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION.  MR WOHLEGEMUTH ADVISED THEY WILL CHECK ALL THE OTHER NEW CARS PRIOR TO LOADING FOR THE SAME CONDITION.  THE VALVE IS A "UTLX UR2236 TT3" 160 PSIG 400F.

column168: SPECIAL AGENT VERN LIBBY WAS NOTIFIED THAT TRAILER REAZ 237094, LOADED ON FLATCAR TTAX 780343 WAS NOTED LEAKING BY BA BISSELL, TERMINAL MANAGER, UNION PACIFIC MOTOR FREIGHT, SEATTLE, AT 1530 HOURS. 08/21/95/. INVESTIGATION DEVELOPED INADEQUATE BLOCKING AND BRACING TO BE VERTICAL AND FALLING OUT, WHEN THE RIGHT REAR DOOR WAS OPENED. FURTHER, INSPECTION NOTED 4 OF 8 330 GALLONS METAL TOTES TO BE LEAKING AT THE MANWAY COVER. ALSO NOTED 13 OF 15 POLY DRUMS WITH LIQUID AROUND THE BUNGS.  SAHM LIBBY CONTACTED JOHN MUNDHENK, PETROLITE CHEMICAL, BAYPORT, TX.  HE IN TURN CONTACTED FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL, SEATTLE TO CLEAN FLATCAR TTAX 780343 AND CLEAN, SECURE CONTAINERS AND OVERPAC ANY THAT MAY NEED IT.  DURING THE CLEANUP OPERATION MEL FRANK, FOSS'S SITE SUPERVISOR ADVISED 13 OF 15 POLY DRUMS WERE NOTED WITH THE BUNGS LOOSE REQUIRING TIGHTENING AND WIPING DOWN.  HE ADVISED THE 16 METAL DRUMS REMAINING WERE OK.  HOWEVER, 3 OF THEM HAD THE EXTERIOR CLEANED AND WIPED DUE TO SPILLAGE FROM THE METAL TOTES.  FURTHER, MEL ADVISED HE FOUND THE FOLLOWING LISTED TOTES WITH THE EXCEPTION(S) THAT FOLLOWS: TOTE #4575 2" AND 3" CLOSURE LOOSE. BOTH SECURED. TOTE #4582 2" AND 3" CLOSURE LOOSE.  BOTH SECURED. ALSO NOTED MANWAY MISAPPLIED. GASKET REPLACED. TOTE #4574 2" AND 3" CLOSURE LOOSE.  BOTH SECURED.  ALOS REPLACED MANWAY GASKET. TOTE #1689 2" CLOSURE LOOSE. SECURED. TOTE #1955 NOTED IN GOOD CONDITION. NO EXCEPTION TOTE #2524 3" CLOSURE LOOSE . TEFLON TAPED AND SECURED TOTE #4580 2" AND 3" CLOSURE LOOSE. BOTH SECURED. ALSO NOTED 9" GAP IN MANWAY GASKET. GASKET REPLACED TOTE #4584 2" AND 3" CLOSURE LOOSE.  BOTH SECURED.  ALSO NOTED 6" GAP IN MANWAY GASKET.  GASKET REPLACED. MEL FRANK, FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL, SEATTLE CONTACTED MIKE HEADLEY PERTROLITE CHEMICALS(713)2913233. REFERENCE THESE EXCEPTIONS.  MEL ALSO ADVISED PORTION OF THE FLOOR IN TRAILER REAZ 237094 HAD TO BE REMOVED, ACCOUNT CONTAMINATION.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT BRAD BISSELL, CONTACTED PETROLITE CHEMICAL AND ADVISED THEM THEY NEEDED TO CONTRACT WITH ARTIC PACK, SEATTLE TO TRANSLOAD THIS SHIPMENT INTO ANOTHER TRAILER FOR CONTINUATION TO DESTINATION. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE DRIVER CALLED IN ON 08/22/95 @3:00OPM STATING HE WAS IN TEXAKANA COMING INTO THE YARD.  HE WAS INFORMED THAT HE HAD A 6:00 AM FOREMAN ARKANSAS LOAD TO DELIVER ON 08/23/95 WHICH WAS ALREADY PRELOADED & READY FOR HIM TO HOOK ON TO.  FROM THIS POINT UNTIL THE ACCIDENT WE HEARD NOTHING FROM THE DRIVER.  HE HAD PLENTY OF TIME TO GET TO THE YARD, TAKE HIS 8HOUR BREAK AND MAKE HIS 6:00 AM APPOINTMENT. UPON SPEAKING WITH THE DRIVER AFTER THE ACCIDENT, HE STATED HE WASN'T SURE WHAT HAPPENED, BUT HE MUST HAVE FALLEN ASLEEP. HE RAN OFF THE ROAD TO THE RIGHT, AND UPON TRYING TO RECOVER HE OVERSTEERED BACK LEFT AND THE TRAILER THEN BEGAN TO SKID SIDEWAYS, AT WHICH TIME THE TRUCK AND TRAILER OVERTURNED ONE TIME COMING TO REST PARTIALLY ONTHE ROADWAYU AND PARTIALLY IN THE DITCH ONTHE SOUTH SIDE OF THE INTERSTATE.  UPON NOTIFICATION WE WERE INFORMED THAT A PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ON A DOME WAS LOOSENED DURING THE ROLL, BUT WAS DISCOVERED BY THE DRIVER UPON GETTING OUT OF THE VEHICLE AND WAS TIGHTENED, STOPPING MATERIAL FROM LEAKING.  EMTECH ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WAS DISPATCHED AND ON THE SCENE WITHIN FIVE HOURS.  MIKE CLOONEN(VICE PRESIDENT AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR.) AND MYSELF WERE ON THE SCENE WITHIN 31/2 HOURS FROM NOTIFICATION.  UPON GIVING THE EMERGENCY PERSONNEL THE INFORMATION THEY NEEDED, I LEFT AND PICKED THE DRIVER UP FROM THE HOSPITAL AND TOOK HIM THE LOCAL DPS OFFICE TO SPEAK WITH THE LICENSE AND WEIGHT OFFICER. MR CLOONEN STATYED AT THE ACCIDENT SCENE WITH THE EMERGENCY PERSONNEL AND HAZMAT TEAM UNTIL THE CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETE. ALL OF THE PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED EITHER FROM THE SCENE OR FROM OUR TEXAS OFFICE.  THE TRUCK AND TRAILER HAS BEEN COMPLETELY GONE OVER AND NO DEFECTS WERE FOUND.  THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED ON 08/28/95.  AS FOR ACTION TO PREVENT FURTHER ACCIDENTS WE HOLD REGULAR MEETINGS WITH ALL OF OUR DRIVERS AND HAVE TOLD ALL OF THEM TIME AND TIME AGAIN THAT IF THEY GET TIRED, PULL OVER, LET US KNOW IF THEY ARE GOING TO BE LATE AND GO TO SLEEP. WE WOULD MUCH RATHER HAVE THEM GET TO THE DESTINATION LATE THAN NOT AT ALL.  SINCE THE ACCIDENT I HAVE AGAIN EMPHASIZED THIS POINT.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY TIM WILCOX, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, STOCKTON, CALIFORNIA, THAT A TANK CAR WAS NOTED LEAKING BY THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT FORCES WHEL INSPECTING AN INTERCHANGE TRAIN.  THE CAR WAS LEFT IN YARD TRACK #31 AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  SYO WILCOX FURTHER STATED THE CAR HAD BEEN IN A CUT OF CARS THAT WAS BEING DELIVERED TO THE EAST STOCKTON YARD, WHEN THE LOCOMOTIVE AND SEVERAL OTHER RAIL CARS DERAILED.  THIS TANK CAR DID NOT DERAIL, HOWEVER, IT IS SUSPECTED THE LEAK OCCURRED DURING THE DERAILMENT ACTION.  MANAGER COOPER ARRANGED TRANSPORTATION TO STOCKTON, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT.  THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD GATX VENT ASSEMBLY WITH A TRIVENT DEFLECTOR, WAS MOUNT ON TOP OF THE MANWAY COVER PLATE.  THE SAFETY VENT WAS DISASSEMBLED, AND THE BURST DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE 100 POUND STAINLESS/TEFLON BS&B DISC.  THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE ALSO INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  DUE TO THE AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR INFORMATIONAL PURPOSES.

DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY DENNY YARD, OPERATIONS MANAGER, ITS INTERMODAL OPERATIONS, LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA, WHO ADVISED HIS RAMP DRIVERS HAD OBSERVED LIQUID LEAKING THROUGH THE FLOORING NEAR THE NOSE OF A CONTAINER WHILE IT WAS BEING GROUNDED FROM THE NOSE OF A CONTAINER WHILE IT WAS BEING GROUNDED FROM THE TRAIN.  THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO TRAILER STORAGE LOT #16 WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  THE CONTAINER ARRIVED IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  THE CONTAINER ARRIVED LOS ANGELES ON THE APLA6Z-29 AT 1200 HOURS, TUESDAY, AUGUST 1, 1995.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE INTERMODAL FACILITY AND FOUND THE CONTAINER PLACARDED AS A CLASS 9 MISCELLANEOUS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND MARINE POLLUTANT.  THE SEALS, DM 487113 AND APL-WDH1329895 WERE REMOVED FROM THE RIGHT REAR DOOR OF THE TWENTY FOOT CONTAINER TO ACCESS AND INSPECT THE LADING.  THE LADING CONSISTED OF METAL 55-GALLON DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED THROUGH THE CONTAINER WITH A STRAIGHT 4 DRUM PER ROW PATTERN.  THE DRUMS WERE PROTECTED WITH A FLOOR SHEET AND THE DOUBLE STACK PATTERN SEPARATED WITH A 1/2 INCH SHEET OF PLYWOOD.  THERE WAS A BULK HEAD AT THE REAR OF THE LADING BETWEEN THE DRUMS AND THE DOORWAY, HOWEVER, IT WAS NOT SECURED TO THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER.  THE BULK HEAD WAS HELD IN PLACE AGAINST THE DRUMS BY THREE 2 X 6 PIECES OF LUMBER THAT WERE NESTED INTO THE CORRUGATED SLOTS OF THE CONTAINER'S SIDE WALLS.  IT APPEARED THE BLOCKING AND BRACING WAS ADEQUATE TO SECURE THE LADING.  AS THE LADING WAS DOUBLE STACKED WITHIN THE CONTAINER,IT WOULD REQUIRE REMOVING THE ENTIRE CONTENTS IN ORDER TO LOCATE THE LEAKING DRUM.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH AMERICAN PRESIDENT LINES AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO PROVIDE AN EMPTY CONTAINER THAT THE LADING COULD BE TRANSLOADED OPERATION.  ON WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 2, 1995, THE CONTAINER WAS PLACED ON THE GROUND IN ORDER TO OFF LOAD THE CONTENTS. UPON REMOVING THE DRUMS, A SINGLE DRUM WAS LOCATED FROM THE BOTTOM STACK, THREE ROWS DEEP INTO THE CONTAINER, AGAINST THE LEFT WALL.  THE DRUM HAD A DENT, POSSIBLY FROM A FORK LIFT BLADE, ON THE SIDE WALL, ROUGHLY TWO INCHES ABOVE THE BOTTOM CHIME.  THE DENT WAS APPROXIMATELY AN EIGHT INCH LONGATED OVAL SHAPE.  THE METAL HAD CRIMPED AT ONE END OF THE DENT, WHERE THE METAL FATIGUED AND SPLIT, WHICH THEN TORE FOR AN ADDITIONAL FOUR INCHES AROUND THE SIDE WALL OF THE DRUM.  DUE TO THE LOCATION OF THE TEAR, THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM WAS LOST.  DURING THE TRANSLOADING OPERATION, AN ADDITIONAL SIX DRUMS WERE LOCATED THAT WERE IN SUCH POOR CONDITION,THEY WERE PLACED INTO OVERPACK DRUMS IN ORDER TO PREVENT POSSIBLE FUTURE FAILURES DURING TRANSIT.  THE TORN DRUMS WERE TO BE SHIPPED.  AS THE WOOD FLOORING IN THE CONTAINER HAD ABSORBED THE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM, AND DECONING THE FLOOR COULD NOT GUARANTEE TOTAL REMOVAL OF THE PRODUCT, THE FLOOR WAS REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL.  THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE LOADED INTO CONTAINER APLS 291811 FOR DELIVERY ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  DU

DEAN COOPER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY DENNY YARD, OPERATIONS MANAGER, ITS INTERMODAL OPERATIONS, LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA, WHO ADVISED HIS RAMP DRIVERS HAD OBSERVED LIQUID LEAKING THROUGH THE FLOORING NEAR THE NOSE OF A CONTAINER WHILE IT WAS BEING GROUNDED FROM THE TRAIN.  THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO TRAILER STORAGE LOT #16, WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  THE CONTAINER ARRIVED LOS ANGELES ON THE APLA6Z-29 AT 1200 HOURS, TUESDAY, AUGUST 1,1995. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE INTERMODAL FACILITY AND FOUND THE CONTAINER PLACARDED AS A CLASS 9, MISCELLANEOUS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND MARINE POLLUTANT.  THE SEALS, DM 485021 AND APL-WDH 132792 WERE REMOVED FROM THE RIGHT REAR DOOR OF THE TWENTY FOOT CONTAINER TO ACCESS AND INSPECT THE LADING.  THE LADING CONSISTED OF METAL 55 DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED THROUGHOUT THE CONTAINER WITH A STRAIGHT 4 DRUM PER ROW PATTERN.  THE DRUMS WERE PROTECTED WITH A FLOOR SHEET AND THE DOUBLE STACK PATTERN SEPARATED WITH A 1/2 INCH SHEET OF PLYWOOD.  THERE WAS A BULK HEAD AT THE REAR OF THE LADING BETWEEN THE DRUMS AND THE DOORWAY, HOWEVER, IT WAS NOT SECURED TO THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER.  THE BULK HEAD WAS HELD IN PLACE AGAINST THE DRUMS BY THREE 2 X 6 PIECES OF LUMBER THAT WERE NESTED INTO THE CORRUGATED SLOTS OF THE CONTAINER'S SIDE WALLS.  IT APPEARED THE BLOCKING AND BRACING WAS ADEQUATE TO SECURE THE LADING.  AS THE LADING WAS DOUBLE STACKED WITHIN THE CONTAINER, IT WOULD REQUIRE REMOVING THE ENTIRE CONTENTS IN ORDER TO LOCATE THE LEAKING DRUM.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH AMERICAN PRESIDENT LINES AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO PROVIDE AN EMPTY CONTAINER THAT THE LADING COULD BE TRANSLOAD OPERATION.  ON WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 2, 1995, THE CONTAINER WAS PLACED ON THE GROUND IN ORDER TO OFF LOAD THE CONTENTS.  UPON REMOVING THE DRUMS, A SINGLE DRUM WAS LOCATED FROM THE BOTTOM STACK, IN THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER, AGAINST THE RIGHT WALL.  THE DRUM HAD A DENT, POSSIBLY FROM A FORK LIFT BLADE, ON THE SIDE WALL, ROUGHLY TWO INCHES ABOVE THE BOTTOM CHIME.  THE DENT WAS APPROXIMATELY A TEN INCH LONGATED OVAL SHAPE.  THE METAL HAD CRIMPED AT BOTH ENDS OF THE DENT, AND THE CRIMP FATIGUED AND SPLIT, WHICH TEN ALLOWED THE METAL TO TEAR AN ADDITIONAL SEVEN DRUMS WERE LOCATED THAT WERE IN SUCH QUESTIONABLE CONDITION, THEY WERE PLACED INTO OVERPACK DRUMS IN ORDER TO PREVENT POSSIBLE FUTURE FAILURES DURING TRANSIT.  THE TORN DRUM WAS ALSO PLACED INTO A OVERPACK AND TRANSPORTED AND STORED PENDING INSTRUCTION FROM DOW AS TO WHERE THE DRUMS ARE TO BE SHIPPED.  THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE LOADED INTO CONTAINER APLS 277553 FOR DELIVERY ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  AS THE WOOD FLOORING IN THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER HAD ABSORBED THE CONTENTS OF THE LEAKING DRUM, IDENTIFIED AS DOWTHERM A, A HEAT TRANSFER FLUID, AND DECONING THE FLOOR COULD NOT GUARANTEE TOTAL REMOVAL OF THE PRODUCT, THE FLOOR WAS REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL.  DUE TO MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT LOST NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO THE ORIGIN SHIPPER.

ON AUGUST 12, 1995 AT APPROXIMATELY 9:45PM AN EMPTY CALCIUM CARBIDE FLO-BIN RUPTURED. THE FLO-BIN WAS LOADED ON A FLATBED WITH A TRACTOR TRAILER HITCHED. THE FLO-BIN HAD BEEN SECURED WITH A STANDARD CARGO CHAIN. THE WEATHER AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT WAS RAINING WITH CALM WINDS. THE FLO-BIN APPEARED TO HAVE HAD CALCIUM CARBIDE RESIDUE INTERNALLY. AFTER THE INCIDENT THE LID OF THE FLO-BIN WAS VISUALLY INSPECTED AND WAS NOTED THAT IT WAS CORRODED AND HAD PIN HOLES. CONCEIVABLY THE CORROSION ALLOWED THE MOISTURE OF THE RAIN TO PENETRATE THE FLO-BIN PRODUCING PRESSURE BUILD UP WHICH IN TURN CAUSED THE LID TO RUPTURE. A CLERK WORKING AT THE CHEVRON TRUCK STOP NOTIFIED THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES, COMBES POLICE DEPARTMENT. CPD ARRIVED AT THE SCENE APPROXIMATELY 10:00PM AND NOTICED SMOKE COMING OUT OF THE FLO-BIN. THE CPD OFFICER CONTACTED HALLINGEN FIRE DEPARTMENT WHICH CONTACTED THE LOCAL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, CODE-3 INC. AN OAC REPRESENTATIVE, ANASTACIO DE LEON WAS CALLED APPROXIMATELY 10:10PM AND ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT 10:20PM. WHEN MR. DE LEON ARRIVED AT THE SCENE THE HARLINGTON FIRE DEPARTMENT PLACED A PLASTIC COVER OVER THE FLO-BINS ON THE TRAILER. MR. DE LEON ADVISED THE AUTHORITIES THAT THE FLO-BINS WERE USED TO TRANSPORT CALCIUM CARBIDE AND THAT THE FLO-BINS WERE CONSIDERED TO BE EMPTY. AOC DRIVER, SANTIAGO ALVAREZ ARRIVED AT THE SCENE APPROXIMATELY 12:00AM. MR. ALVAREX WAS QUESTIONED BY THE AUTHORITIES AND WAS REQUESTED TO PRODUCE HIS TRUCK MANIFEST. MR. ALVAREZ WAS ASKED TO REMOVE HIS VEHICLE AND TRAILER FROM THE VICINITY. APPROXIMATELY 1:00AM, THE AUTHORITIES AT THE SCENE ESCORTED MR. ALVARAZ AND HIS VEHICLE TO AN ISOLATED AREA, DESIGNATED BY DPS, IN THE NEIGHBORING COUNTY OF WILLACY, APPROXIMATELY 15 MILES TO THE NORTH OF THE SCENE. APPROXIMATELY 2:15AM, MR. ALVAREZ WAS LEFT AT THE ISOLATED AREA AND INSTRUCTED TO WAIT FOR THE ARRRIVAL OF THE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION INVESTIGATOR. AFTER WAITING APPROXIMATELY (9) NINE HOURS FOR A DOT INVESTIGATOR TO ARRIVE AT THE ISOLATED AREA AOC DIRECTOR OF SAFETY, MR. RICHARD DI CANTU WAS CONTACTED. MR. DI CANTU CONTACTED MR. LEE THOMPSON, CODE-3 TO DISCUSS THE STATUS OF THE DOT REPORT. MR. LEE THOMPSON AUTHORIZED MR. DI CANTU TO MOVE THE AOC VEHICLE AND FLO-BINS, APPROXIMATELY 12:00PM. MR. ALVAREZ THEN PROCEEDED TO TRANSPORT THE FLO-BINS TO THE AOC PLANT ON BUS 83 IN HARLINGEN. PREVENTIVE MEASURES; AOC HAS TAKEN THE FOLLOWING ACTIONS TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS. AOC CONTACTED THE CALCIUM CARBIDE VENDOR, ELKEM OF AMERICA, FOR ASSISTANCE WITH THE SAFETY, HANDLING AND THE RE-QUALIFICATION OF AOC OWNED FLO-BINS. AOC OWNED FLO-BINS WERE TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE FOR INSPECTION. ALL OAC OWNED FLO-BINS ARE CURRENTLY BEING INSPECTED, REPAIRED IF NEEDED, PAINTED, LABELED. SERIALIZED AND REQUALIFIED. AOC OWNED FLO-BINS NOT PASSING RE-QUALIFICATION WILL BE CONDEMNED AND SCRAPPED. PLANT WORKERS WERE RE-INSTRUCTED ON PROCEDURES ON THE HANDLING, VISUAL CHECKING, SERVICING AND TRACKING OF FLO-BINS.
